Xpath:
    1.  Absolute Xpath
            Is a direct way to find an element in HTML or XML code.
            It uses the complete path from the root element to the desired element.

            /html/body/div/div/div/div/div/div/div[2]/div/div/form/div/div/input


    2.  Relative Xpath
            Relative XPath begins with a double forward slash //
            and can search for an element anywhere on the webpage2.
            Relative XPaths are generally preferred as they are not complete paths from the root node1.

            attribute => //tagname[@attribute='value']
            text => //tagname[text()='value']
            contains =>  attribute -> //tagname[contains(@name,'value')]
                         text -> //tagname[contains(text(),'value')]

            startswith =>   attribute -> //tagname[starts-with(@attribute, 'value')]
                            text -> //tagname[starts-with(text(), 'value'0]

            indexing => (//tagname[@attribute='value'])[1]

            and operator => //tagname[@attribute='value' and @attribute='value']